<TITLE> Mashrafe ruled out of ODI series </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 20 (bdnews24.com)  Bangladesh captain Mashrafe Bin Mortaza has been ruled out of the three-match one-day international series against the West Indies following his knee injury. Bangladesh pace spearhead Mashrafe along with paceman Shahadat Hossain, left-arm spinner Enamul Haq Junior and wicketkeeper Sahagir Hossain will return home after the end of the second and final Test on Wednesday, said a BCB press release on Monday. Pacer Nazmul Hossain had already reached West Indies as back-up for Mashrafe before the start of the second and final Test. Others will be replaced by pacer Syed Rasel, left-arm spinner Abdur Razzak and all-rounder Naeem Islam, the trio were supposed to reach Grenada on Monday after leaving country on Sunday evening. Bangladesh will take on the hosts in the first ODI on July 26 while the second and third ODIs are scheduled to be held on July 28 and July 31. Mashrafe sustained right knee injury on the third day of the first Test and then never bowled a single ball against the hosts though he batted in Bangladesh's second innings and also sat out the second and final Test. The 25-year old pacer underwent an MRI exam on July 14 in Grenada and the initial report suggested he had a muscle stress in the knee and the report was sent to orthopedic Australian surgeon Dr. David Young for his expert opinion. Mashrafe is till nursing the knee injury and continue with his recovery, said a BCB statement. bdn
